# AI Security Modules — Platform Extension Spec
## Context
This platform already covers: DevSecOps pipeline integration,
DAST, API security, ASM (attack surface management), multi-chain
exploit chaining, compliance reporting.
We are adding two new verticals:
1. LLM / AI Application Red Teaming
2. MCP (Model Context Protocol) Security Scanner
These must integrate with existing: task management, reporting
engine, compliance mapper, discovery engine.
---
## Module 1: LLM Red Teaming Engine
### What it tests
- Prompt Injection (direct and indirect via RAG/tool output)
- Jailbreaks (role-play, DAN, system prompt override attempts)
- System Prompt Extraction
- Data Leakage through context windows
- Insecure Output Handling (XSS via LLM output, code injection)
- Excessive Agency (agent takes unauthorized actions)
- Model Denial of Service (token flooding, recursive prompts)
- Training Data Poisoning indicators
- Multi-turn manipulation chains (not single-payload)
### Compliance mapping (auto-tag every finding to)
- OWASP LLM Top 10 2025 (LLM01–LLM10)
- NIST AI RMF (Govern, Map, Measure, Manage)
- EU AI Act risk classification (minimal/limited/high/unacceptable)
- MITRE ATLAS technique IDs
### Input targets
- REST API endpoints that call an LLM
- Chat interface URLs (web scraping + interaction)
- Direct model API keys (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, local Ollama)
- LangChain / LlamaIndex app endpoints
- RAG pipeline endpoints
### Output
- Severity-rated findings (Critical/High/Medium/Low)
- Reproduction steps (exact prompt chain that triggered issue)
- Compliance tag per finding
- Remediation guidance (guardrail recommendations)
- Feeds into existing platform reporting engine
### Architecture
- Attack module: payload library (curated + AI-generated variants)
- Orchestrator: multi-turn conversation manager
- Judge layer: LLM-as-judge to evaluate if attack succeeded
- Result normalizer: maps to existing finding schema
