## Module 2: MCP Security Scanner
### What it tests
Tool Poisoning
- Malicious instructions hidden in tool name/description metadata
- Rug-pull attacks (tool behavior changes post-approval)
- Shadow tool injection via tool output
Identity & Authentication
- Missing auth on MCP server endpoints
- Token/credential exposure in tool responses
- Broken identity binding (wrong provider tool execution)
Permission & Access Control
- Overprivileged tool scopes
- Unauthorized cross-tool data flow
- Agent accessing resources beyond declared scope
Data Exposure
- PII leakage through tool responses
- Sensitive data in tool metadata
- Insecure logging of tool inputs/outputs
Infrastructure
- Publicly exposed MCP server endpoints (no auth)
- Default credentials on MCP deployments
- Transport security (missing TLS, weak cipher suites)
- SSRF via tool URL parameters
Multi-Server Composition risks
- Tool name collision across servers
- Trust boundary violations between MCP servers
- A2A protocol trust chain weaknesses
### Compliance mapping
- CIS MCP Security Guide (April 2026)
- OWASP LLM Top 10 (LLM07 Insecure Plugin Design)
- NIST AI RMF
- SOC 2 Type II control mapping
### Input targets
- MCP server URLs / local socket paths
- Tool schema / manifest JSON
- MCP client config files (Claude Desktop, VS Code, etc.)
- Docker/K8s deployed MCP containers
### Output
- Attack surface map (all tools, permissions, data flows)
- Vulnerability findings with CVSS scoring
- Tool permission matrix (what each agent can reach)
- Compliance tag per finding
- Feeds into existing ASM and reporting modules
### Architecture
- Discovery: enumerate all MCP servers, tools, schemas
- Static analysis: parse tool descriptions for poisoning indicators
- Dynamic testing: connect as client, probe each tool
- Permission mapper: build graph of agent → tool → data access
- Result normalizer: maps to existing finding schema
